<div class='communityQuestionSubTitle'>
Popular Answered Questions
</div>
<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1652135-i-would-like-to-read-this-book-but-i-am">I would like to read this book, but I am hestitant. I know the movie promotes the &#39;lost cause&#39; ideology. (ie: the south rebelled not because of slavery, but for states rights and &#39;freedom&#39;) Does the book promote this idea as well?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1652135'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F29925.Gods_and_Generals">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1652135-i-would-like-to-read-this-book-but-i-am">one year ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1652135-i-would-like-to-read-this-book-but-i-am">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/8574952-nat-medlen"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/8574952-nat-medlen">Nat Medlen</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">It mentions this idea, it must to have any reliability in the historic genre. However, it does not stress this as a reason. It spends much more time l<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">It mentions this idea, it must to have any reliability in the historic genre. However, it does not stress this as a reason. It spends much more time looking into the lives of many of the leaders. Some of the ones from the South fight for the cause of slavery, but some of them don't. Some of the ones from the North fight for the ideological point of view of ending slavery, while some of them simply fight as duty to their country or to preserve the Union. I hope that helps.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

